<p>You can enable the Cast integration by going to the Integrations page inside the config panel.</p>
<h2>Home Assistant Cast</h2>
<p>Home Assistant has its own Cast application to show the Home Assistant UI on any Chromecast device.  You can use it by adding the <a href="/lovelace/entities/#cast">Cast entity row</a> to your Lovelace UI, or by calling the <code>cast.show_lovelace_view</code> service. The service takes the path of a Lovelace view and an entity ID of a Cast device to show the view on. A <code>path</code> has to be defined in your Lovelace YAML for each view, as outlined in the <a href="/lovelace/views/#path">views documentation</a>.</p>
<pre><code class="language-json">{
  &quot;entity_id&quot;: &quot;media_player.office_display_4&quot;,
  &quot;view_path&quot;: &quot;lights&quot;
}
</code></pre>
<p>Note that Home Assistant Cast requires your Home Assistant installation to be accessible via <code>https://</code>. If youâ€™re using Home Assistant Cloud, you donâ€™t need to do anything. Otherwise you must make sure that you have configured the <code>base_url</code> for <a href="/integrations/http/">the <code>http</code> integration</a>.</p>
<h2>Advanced use</h2>
<p>Cast devices can only be discovered if they are on the same subnet as Home Assistant. If this is not the case, you need to configure the IP address of the Cast device directly:</p>
<pre><code class="language-yaml"># Example configuration.yaml entry
cast:
  media_player:
    - host: 192.168.1.10
</code></pre>
